Dockerfile Best Practices — Layers, Caching, .dockerignore
How Layers Work
Every RUN, COPY, ADD instruction creates a new layer. Layers are:

Cached — reused if nothing above changed
Stacked — each layer adds to the image size
Immutable — even if you delete a file in a later layer, it still exists in the earlier layer (size not reduced)

FROM ubuntu              ← Layer 1: 78MB
RUN apt-get update       ← Layer 2: +32MB
RUN apt-get install -y curl  ← Layer 3: +12MB
COPY app.py /app/        ← Layer 4: +1KB

Hands-On: Start with a BAD Dockerfile
Step 1 — Create a deliberately bad Dockerfile
mkdir ~/dockerfile-optimize && cd ~/dockerfile-optimize

cat > app.py <<'EOF'
from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route("/")
def home():
    return "Optimized Docker App!"

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)
EOF

cat > requirements.txt <<'EOF'
flask==3.0.0
EOF

# BAD Dockerfile — all anti-patterns
cat > Dockerfile.bad <<'EOF'
FROM ubuntu

RUN apt-get update
RUN apt-get install -y python3
RUN apt-get install -y python3-pip
RUN apt-get install -y curl wget vim nano git

COPY . /app

RUN pip3 install flask

WORKDIR /app

CMD ["python3", "app.py"]
EOF

# Build bad version
docker build -f Dockerfile.bad -t flask-bad:v1 .
docker images flask-bad        # note the SIZE

Hands-On: Apply Best Practices One by One
Practice 1 — Use a Specific Slim Base Image

# ubuntu = 78MB base, full OS
# python:3.11 = 900MB+ (has build tools)
# python:3.11-slim = 130MB (no extras)
# python:3.11-alpine = 23MB (musl libc, minimal)

docker pull python:3.11
docker pull python:3.11-slim
docker pull python:3.11-alpine

docker images python           # compare sizes side by side

Practice 2 — Combine RUN commands (fewer layers)
# BAD — 3 separate layers, apt cache left behind
RUN apt-get update
RUN apt-get install -y curl
RUN apt-get install -y wget

# GOOD — 1 layer, cache cleaned in same layer
RUN apt-get update && \
    apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends curl wget && \
    rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

Practice 3 — Order layers by change frequency
# BAD — any code change re-installs all dependencies
COPY . /app
RUN pip install -r /app/requirements.txt

# GOOD — dependencies cached unless requirements.txt changes
COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt
COPY app.py .         ← changes often, stays at bottom

Practice 4 — Create the GOOD Dockerfile
cat > Dockerfile.good <<'EOF'
# Best practice 1: specific slim base image
FROM python:3.11-slim

# Best practice 2: set WORKDIR early
WORKDIR /app

# Best practice 3: copy dependencies BEFORE source code
COPY requirements.txt .

# Best practice 4: install with no cache, combine in one RUN
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

# Best practice 5: copy app source last (changes most often)
COPY app.py .

# Best practice 6: run as non-root user
RUN useradd -m appuser
USER appuser

# Best practice 7: document the port
EXPOSE 5000

# Best practice 8: use exec form (not shell form)
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
EOF

docker build -f Dockerfile.good -t flask-good:v1 .
docker images | grep flask     # compare bad vs good sizes

Hands-On: .dockerignore Deep Dive
Step 1 — See what enters build context without .dockerignore
# Add junk files to simulate a real project
mkdir -p .git node_modules __pycache__
echo "SECRET_KEY=abc123" > .env
dd if=/dev/urandom of=bigfile.bin bs=1M count=10   # 10MB dummy file
touch test_app.py debug.log

# Build and watch "Sending build context" size
docker build -f Dockerfile.good -t flask-nignore:v1 .
# Sending build context to Docker daemon  XX MB  ← watch this

Step 2 — Add .dockerignore
cat > .dockerignore <<'EOF'
# Version control
.git
.gitignore

# Python artifacts
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
*.pyd
.pytest_cache/

# Environment & secrets
.env
*.env

# Test files
test_*.py
*_test.py

# Logs & temp
*.log
*.tmp
bigfile.bin

# Node (if mixed project)
node_modules/

# IDE
.vscode/
.idea/
EOF

# Rebuild — notice smaller build context
docker build -f Dockerfile.good -t flask-withignore:v1 .
# Sending build context to Docker daemon  X KB  ← much smaller

Hands-On: Multi-Stage Build to Minimize Size
cat > Dockerfile.multistage <<'EOF'
# ---- Stage 1: Builder ----
FROM python:3.11 AS builder
WORKDIR /build

COPY requirements.txt .
# Install to a local dir, not system
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --prefix=/install -r requirements.txt

# ---- Stage 2: Runtime ----
FROM python:3.11-slim AS runtime
WORKDIR /app

# Copy only installed packages from builder
COPY --from=builder /install /usr/local

# Copy app
COPY app.py .

RUN useradd -m appuser
USER appuser

EXPOSE 5000
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
EOF

docker build -f Dockerfile.multistage -t flask-multistage:v1 .

# Compare all versions
docker images | grep flask
# flask-bad         →  huge
# flask-good        →  medium
# flask-multistage  →  smallest

Hands-On: Verify Caching in Action
# Build once
docker build -f Dockerfile.good -t flask-cache:v1 .

# Change only app.py
echo "# new comment" >> app.py

# Rebuild — watch which steps say CACHED
docker build -f Dockerfile.good -t flask-cache:v2 .
# Step 1: FROM       → CACHED
# Step 2: WORKDIR    → CACHED
# Step 3: COPY req   → CACHED
# Step 4: RUN pip    → CACHED  ← key! no reinstall
# Step 5: COPY app   → not cached (file changed)

# Now change requirements.txt
echo "requests==2.31.0" >> requirements.txt

# Rebuild — pip install is no longer cached
docker build -f Dockerfile.good -t flask-cache:v3 .
# Step 4: RUN pip    → not cached (runs again)

Summary: Cheat Sheet
BAD                              GOOD
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FROM ubuntu                      FROM python:3.11-slim
RUN apt update                   RUN apt update && apt install -y pkg \
RUN apt install -y pkg               && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
COPY . /app                      COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install -r req.txt       RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r req.txt
                                 COPY app.py .
No .dockerignore                 .dockerignore excludes .git, __pycache__, .env
No non-root user                 RUN useradd -m user && USER user
CMD python app.py (shell form)   CMD ["python", "app.py"] (exec form)
Single-stage build               Multi-stage for compiled/heavy apps

Interview Questions & Answers
Q1. How does Docker layer caching work?

Docker caches each instruction layer. On rebuild, if a layer's instruction AND all inputs (files, args) are unchanged, Docker reuses the cache. Any change invalidates that layer and all layers below it.

Q2. Why should you copy requirements.txt before source code?

Dependencies change rarely; source code changes often. Copying requirements first means the pip install layer is cached unless requirements.txt changes — saving minutes on every rebuild.

Q3. Why can't you reduce image size by deleting files in a later RUN?

Each RUN creates a new layer. The file still exists in the earlier layer and is counted in image size. To truly remove it, delete in the same RUN command that created it.

Q4. What is the difference between shell form and exec form of CMD?

Shell form: CMD python app.py — runs via /bin/sh -c, PID 1 is sh, signals not forwarded to app.
Exec form: CMD ["python", "app.py"] — app is PID 1, receives OS signals (SIGTERM) directly. Always prefer exec form.

Q5. Why run containers as non-root?

If a container is compromised, a root process can escape and damage the host. Non-root user limits blast radius — follows principle of least privilege.

Q6. What does .dockerignore do and why does it matter?

Excludes files from build context sent to Docker daemon. Smaller context = faster builds. Also prevents secrets (.env) and large files from entering the image accidentally.

Q7. What is a multi-stage build? When would you use it?

Multiple FROM stages — build tools stay in early stages, only the runtime artifact is in the final image. Use for compiled languages (Go, Java, C++), or when build tools (gcc, npm dev deps) shouldn't be in production.

Q8. What does --no-cache-dir do in pip?

Prevents pip from writing downloaded packages to a local cache dir. Since the cache is useless inside an image layer, this saves space.

Q9. What is --no-install-recommends in apt?

Tells apt not to install suggested/recommended packages — only installs exactly what you asked for. Reduces image size significantly.

Q10. How would you find which layer is making your image large?

docker history image_name — shows each layer with its size. Identify the large ones and optimize the corresponding Dockerfile instruction.
